1 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario players]]\n[[Category:2018 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for Argentina]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Argentine expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of Spain]]\n[[Category:Argentine fraudsters]]\n[[Category:People convicted of fraud]]\n[[Category:People convicted of tax crimes]]\n[[Category:People named in the Panama Papers]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed cite error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lionel_Messi"}
{"title_page": "Nikolai Volkoff", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name=Nikolai Volkoff\n|birthname=Josip Hrvoje Peruzovi\u0107\n|image=Nikolai Volkoff.jpg\n|caption=Volkoff in 2008\n|names=Nikolai Volkoff<ref name=\"WWEbio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/halloffame/inductees/nikolaivolkoff/|title=Nikolai Volkoff WWE Hall of Fame Profile|accessdate=March 30, 2011|publisher=WWE}}</ref><br />Bepo Mongol<ref name=\"OWOW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/n/nikolai-volkoff.html|title=Nikolai Volkoff Profile|accessdate=September 21, 2008|publisher=Online World Of Wrestling}}</ref><br />Boris Breznikoff<br />Executioner #3\n|height =6 ft 4 in<ref name=\"WWEbio\"/>\n|weight =313 lb<ref name=\"WWEbio\"/>\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1947|10|14}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Summer |first1=Ben |title=Nikolai Volkoff, professional wrestler who played a Soviet villain, dies at 70 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/obituaries/nikolai-volkoff-professional-wrestler-who-played-a-soviet-villain-dies-at-70/2018/07/30/512c755e-93a4-11e8-8ffb-5de6d5e49ada_story.html |accessdate=24 December 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=30 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n|birth_place=[[Split, Croatia|Split]], [[People's Republic of Croatia|PR Croatia]], [[Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]]<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n|children = 2\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2018|07|29|1947|10|14}}\n|death_place= [[Glen Arm, Maryland]], U.S.\n|billed=Moscow, [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russia]]<br>Soviet Union<ref name=\"OWOW\"/><br>[[Mongolia]]\n|trainer=[[Stu Hart]]<ref name=\"WWEbio\"/><br />[[Newton Tattrie]]\n|debut=1967\n|retired=May 5, 2018\n}}\n\n'''Josip Hrvoje Peruzovi\u0107''' (October 14, 1947 \u2013 July 29, 2018),<ref name=Death/><ref>Born in 1946 per search of FamilyTreeNow.com</ref> better known by his [[ring name]] of '''Nikolai Volkoff''', was a [[Croatian Americans|Croatian-American]] [[professional wrestler]] who was best known for his performances in the [[World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF). Although the Volkoff character was often portrayed as a villainous Russian, Peruzovi\u0107 originated from [[Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]].\n\nIn the 1970s, he was Bepo of the Mongols [[tag team]], one of the masked [[The Executioners (professional wrestling)|Executioners]] and feuded with [[Bruno Sammartino]] over the [[WWWF World Heavyweight Championship]] as Volkoff. In the 1980s, he was known for teaming with [[The Iron Sheik]], with whom he won the [[WWF Tag Team Championship]] at the inaugural [[WrestleMania]] event, and later with [[Boris Zhukov]] as [[The Bolsheviks]]. In 1990, he turned [[Face (wrestling)|face]] and embraced America, briefly feuding with Zhukov and newly-turned [[Iraq]]i sympathizer [[Sgt. Slaughter]]. In 1994, after a hiatus, he returned as a destitute and desperate character, exploited by [[Ted DiBiase]] as the first member of his [[Million Dollar Corporation]].\n\n==Early life==\nPeruzovi\u0107 grew up in the [[Socialist Republic of Croatia]], which was then part of [[Federal People's Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/sports/wrestling/did-you-know-that-nikolai-volkoff-ran-for-the-maryland/article_0f5378ca-601a-11e8-b2a1-e3d47d19f018.html|title=Did you know that Nikolai Volkoff ran for the Maryland statehouse?|first=Mike|last=Mooneyham|work=[[The Post and Courier]]|publisher=[[Evening Post Industries]]|location=[[Charleston, South Carolina]]|date=May 27, 2018|accessdate=July 30, 2018}}</ref> His parents were Ivan and Dragica (n\u00e9e Toma\u0161evi\u0107). Despite what he sometimes claimed his actual middle name was not Nikolai but Hrvoje, and his mother's maiden name was not Volkoff but Toma\u0161evi\u0107. These inconsistencies cast doubt on his ethnic background and seem to indicate a Croat ethnicity.<ref name=\"Dragica Peruzovi\u0107 - Osmrtnice.hr\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.osmrtnice.hr/dragica-peruzovic|title=Dragica Peruzovi\u0107 - Osmrtnice.hr|website=Osmrtnice.hr|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/31/obituaries/nikolai-volkoff-soviet-villain-in-the-wrestling-ring-is-dead-at-70.html|title=Nikolai Volkoff, Soviet Villain in the Wrestling Ring, Is Dead at 70|access-date=August 2, 2018|language=en}}</ref> His maternal grandfather Ante Toma\u0161evi\u0107 was world champion in the greco-roman wrestling style at the turn of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hhs.hr/povijest-hrvanja-u-hrvatskoj/|title=Povijest hrvanja u Hrvatskoj|last=www.eternus-web.hr|first=Eternus web -|website=www.hhs.hr|language=hr-HR|access-date=August 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> Ante was born in Cetina, a small village near Sinj, Croatia to Croatian parents Stipe and Katerina in 1872. He was on the Yugoslavian [[Powerlifting|weightlifting]] team until 1967, when he emigrated to Canada after a weightlifting tournament in [[Vienna]], Austria.{{sfn|Grasso|2014|page=332}} He received training in [[Calgary]] from [[Stu Hart]], followed by his arrival in the United States in 1970.<ref name=\"Dragica Peruzovi\u0107 - Osmrtnice.hr\"/>\n\nHis brother is Croatian footballer [[Luka Peruzovi\u0107]]. A fellow Croatian-native played the first Soviet Volkoff character in American pro-wrestling. Steve Gobb, born Gobrokovich, wrestled as USSR's Nicoli Volkoff in the 1960s before the character was picked up by Josip.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Early years (1967\u20131970)===\nWhile trying his luck as a wrestler in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]] in 1967, he met the wrestler [[Geeto Mongol|Newton Tattrie]], who was wrestling for [[Stu Hart]]'s [[Stampede Wrestling]]. During his 1963-1968 tour, Tattrie took Peruzovic under his wing as a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 and trained the non-English speaking, 315-pound man to become a professional wrestler and [[tag team]] partner. When Tattrie left the territory in 1968 for the US, Peruzovic left with him, working in various territories for The [[National Wrestling Alliance]] including [[NWA Detroit]], the [[International Wrestling Association (1970s)|International Wrestling Association]] and the [[National Wrestling Federation]] where they won tag gold.\n\n===World Wide Wrestling Federation (1970\u20131971)===\nIn 1970 he began wrestling in [[Vince McMahon Sr.]]'s World Wide Wrestling Federation (WWWF) (currently known as [[WWE]]). Wrestling as ''Bepo Mongol'', managed by \"Captain\" [[Lou Albano]] and partnered with Newton Tattrie (as Geeto Mongol) as The Mongols, he captured the [[WWF International Tag Team Championship]] from [[Tony Marino]] and [[V\u00edctor Rivera (professional wrestler)|Victor Rivera]] on June 15, 1970.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> After losing the title to [[Grady Johnson|Luke Graham]] and [[Camille Tourville|Tarzan Tyler]] in a match over a year later that unified the WWWF International and [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWWF World Tag Team Championship]], Peruzovic left the WWWF and went on to singles competition under the name \"Nikolai Volkoff\".<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n\n===Return to the WWWF (1974\u20131980)===\nIn 1974, Volkoff returned to the company and appeared in a memorable match at a sold out [[Madison Square Garden]] and wrestled one of the sport's most famous champions, [[Bruno Sammartino]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> In 1976, he was masked as an Executioner as he became the third member along with [[Killer Kowalski]] and [[Big John Studd]]. They captured the World Tag Team Championship, but it was vacated due to a third member interfering. Later he reverted to the Volkoff name. During this time in the WWWF, Volkoff was announced as being from Mongolia. He had a very successful feud with Bruno Sammartino, which started when Volkoff attacked him during an interview segment. They sold-out arenas throughout the Northeast. During this tenure, he began crushing fresh apples with one hand as a sign of what he would do to his opponents. He later had a feud with [[Bob Backlund]] during Backlund's tenure as champion.\n\n===American Wrestling Association; Mid-South; and Japan (1972\u20131984, 1989)===\nLate in 1974, Volkoff moved to the [[American Wrestling Association|AWA]] where he wrestled under the name ''Boris Breznikoff'', managed by [[Bobby \"The Brain\" Heenan]], he used the same gimmick with a different ring name.\n\nFrom 1977 to 1983 he wrestled in Japan for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] and [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]].\n\nIn 1983, Volkoff wrestled for \"Cowboy\" [[Bill Watts]] in the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)#Mid-South Wrestling|Mid-South region]].\n\nOn October 29, 1989 he returned to [[American Wrestling Association|AWA]] for a one night appearance as he lost to [[Ken Patera]].\n\n===Second return to the WWF (1984\u20131990, 1992)===\n==== Teaming with the Iron Sheik (1984&ndash;1987) ====\n{{main|The Iron Sheik and Nikolai Volkoff}}\n[[File:Classy Freddie Blassie.jpg|thumb|Volkoff with [[The Iron Sheik]] and their manager, [[Freddie Blassie]]]]\nIn July 1984, Volkoff returned to the renamed WWF defeating SD Jones on Georgia Championship Wrestling and teamed with [[the Iron Sheik]] with the pair being managed by the \"Hollywood fashion plate\" [[Freddie Blassie|\"Classy\" Freddie Blassie]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> It was at this point that Volkoff began to sing the [[national anthem of the Soviet Union]] before every match after which the Sheik would grab the microphone and proclaim \"Iran number one, Russia number one\" before exaggeratedly spitting after saying \"USA\", in order to gain even more [[heat (professional wrestling)|heat]] for being [[heel (professional wrestling)#Heel Types|foreign heels]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/>\n\nThe new team of Volkoff and the Iron Sheik captured the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] from [[The U.S. Express]] ([[Mike Rotunda|Mike Rotundo]] and [[Barry Windham]]) at the first [[WrestleMania (1985)|WrestleMania]], on March 31, 1985, after the Sheik had knocked out Windham with Fred Blassie's cane.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> After losing the title back to Rotundo and Windham three months later, Volkoff began to wrestle more in singles competition. He faced [[Hulk Hogan]] for the [[WWF World Heavyweight Championship]] on several occasions in 1985 and 1986 (including a [[flag match]] on ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event II]]'' at the [[Brendan Byrne Arena]]).\n\nVolkoff also feuded with former [[82nd Airborne Division|82nd Airborne]] [[paratrooper]] [[Corporal Kirchner]] throughout 1985 and 1986, defeating him in a \"peace match\" on ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event IV]]''. Their feud ended when Kirchner used Blassie's cane to defeat Volkoff at [[WrestleMania 2]] in another flag match during the [[Allstate Arena|Chicago]] portion of the event.\n\nIn the fall of 1986, Volkoff's manager [[Freddie Blassie|\"Classy\" Freddy Blassie]] sold half interest in his stable of superstars to the \"Doctor of Style\", [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]] ([[kayfabe]]),<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> giving Slick co-managerial rights to Volkoff. Blassie also shared the contracts of the Iron Sheik and [[Hercules (wrestler)|Hercules]]. This was a storyline aimed at reducing the aging Blassie's active role, and the \"Hollywood fashion plate\" eventually retired in the fall of 1986 at the age of 68. Sheik and Volkoff feuded with WWF newcomer [[Jim Duggan]] for the majority of 1987, including Duggan running to the ring and stopping the Russian's singing before their match against [[The Killer Bees (professional wrestling)|The Killer Bees]] at [[WrestleMania III]] (Sheik and Volkoff won by disqualification when Duggan entered the ring while chasing Volkoff and then hitting the Sheik with his 2x4 while he had the [[Professional wrestling holds#Camel clutch|camel clutch]] on [[Jim Brunzell|\"Jumping\" Jim Brunzell]]).\n\n==== The Bolsheviks (1987&ndash;1990) ====\n{{main|The Bolsheviks}}\nIn late 1987, Volkoff was teamed with [[Boris Zhukov]], another alleged Russian (actually an American wrestler whose real name was James Harrell), to form [[The Bolsheviks]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> They feuded with WWF newcomers [[The Powers of Pain]], losing to them at the inaugural ''[[SummerSlam]]'' PPV in [[SummerSlam (1988)|1988]], however The Bolsheviks did not gain the success as did his partnership with The Iron Sheik. As they lost the public eye due to many losses, they eventually lost their manager Slick and were used as a comic relief team losing many matches to [[The Bushwhackers]]. The Bolsheviks never held any titles together, and are perhaps best remembered for being defeated in 19 seconds by [[The Hart Foundation]] at [[WrestleMania VI]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> Eventually, by 1990, The Bolsheviks split up. Volkoff publicly ended the partnership prior to a match where he confronted Zhukhov and then started singing \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\", drawing loud cheers from the audience and turning babyface in the process.\n\n==== Babyface turn (1990;1992) ====\nA short time after The Bolsheviks split, Volkoff became a [[face (professional wrestling)|face]] for the first time in his career. His [[List of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] was now that of a recent defector, he became very pro-[[Western world|west]] which led to a feud with [[Sgt. Slaughter]] who had an Iraqi sympathizer role and teamed with the former Iron Sheik, who had recently begun an [[Iraq]]i gimmick under the name Colonel Mustafa.<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> After Volkoff's team defeated Slaughter's team at the [[Survivor Series (1990)|1990 Survivor Series]] ([[Tito Santana]] was the sole survivor), Volkoff left the WWF at the end of 1990.\n\nHe made a brief return to compete in the 1992 [[Royal Rumble (1992)|Royal Rumble]] match, as well as to face Hercules in a house show match on January 29 in Lowell, Massachusetts.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/92.htm</ref>\n\n===Various promotions (1991-1994)===\nAfter leaving WWF, Volkoff began competing in the [[independent circuit]]. On May 3, 1991 he defeated his former Bolshevik partner [[Boris Zhukov]] for Trans World Wrestling Federation in Newington, Connecticut.\n\nOn August 8, 1992 he went to Puerto Rico to wrestled for [[World Wrestling Council]] WCC 19th Anniversario 1992 losing to [[The Patriot (wrestler)|The Patriot]].\n\nOn April 4, 1993 he wrestled his former partner [[The Iron Sheik]] to a double count out at Wrestling in the USA event in Livingston, New Jersey.\n\n===Extreme Championship Wreslting (1992-1993)===\nIn 1992 he went to [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] in Philadelphia where he feuded with Vladimir Markoff. On October 2, he lost to [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW Champion]] [[Don Muraco]].\n\nHe then returned to ECW on October 16, 1993 as he lost to [[Jimmy Snuka]].\n\n===Third return to the WWF (1993;1994-1995)===\n==== One night appearance (1993) ====\nHe returned as a babyface to pin [[Barry Horowitz]] at a ''WWF Superstars''/''All-American Wrestling'' taping on July 6, 1993, in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm</ref>\n\n==== Million Dollar Corporation and departure (1994\u20131995) ====\nOn February 1, 1994, Volkoff began a full-time return to the WWF, making a ringside appearance at a Superstars taping in White Plains, New York during a match between Diesel and Mike Moraldo.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/94.htm</ref> For the next two months, Volkoff was shown in the crowd, until eventually he became a sympathetic heel by playing the whipping-boy of [[Ted DiBiase]]'s [[Million Dollar Corporation]].<ref name=\"OWOW\"/> Volkoff had [[kayfabe]] fallen on hard times and was forced to take a job working for DiBiase and his new Corporation. As low man in the group he was forced to wrestle matches no one else wanted to or sent out to \"soften up\" opponents for other members of the [[List of professional wrestling terms#S|stable]] as the sacrificial lamb of the group. The disrespect even extended to renaming him \"Nickel & Dime\" Volkoff and DiBiase forcing him to place a [[cent (United States coin)|\u00a2]] on his trunks where the Russian [[hammer and sickle|sickle]] once was along with a sign on his ring attire that read \"Property Of The Million Dollar Man\". The final WWF match for Volkoff was on December 30, 1994 when he defeated jobber Bob Starr in a house show.  Volkoff's final appearance was at the WWF's final show at The Boston Garden on May 13, 1995. During a match between WWF Champion Diesel and Sid, Volkoff made an appearance to chase Sid's manager Ted Dibiase away.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/95.htm</ref> Following this last run in the WWF, Volkoff entered a semi-retirement.\n\n===Semi-retirement (1995\u20132018)===\nVolkoff made a brief cameo on an episode of ''[[WWF Shotgun Saturday Night|Shotgun Saturday Night]]'' in 1997 where [[Todd Pettengill]] discovered him [[homelessness|homeless]] sleeping in a box on the streets of New York City. He also appeared at [[WrestleMania X-Seven]] at the [[Astrodome]] in Houston in the gimmick battle royal which was won by [[The Iron Sheik]].\n\nOn November 30, 2001 he lost to [[King Kong Bundy]] at AAWA event in Jersey City, New Jersey.\n\nOn February 3, 2005, Volkoff was announced as one of the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] inductees for the class of 2005. He was inducted on April 2, 2005 by [[Jim Ross]] at the [[Universal Amphitheatre]] in Los Angeles.\n\nIn 2006, Volkoff took part in the [[World Wrestling Legends]] pay-per-view ''6:05 The Reunion''. Managed by the Iron Sheik, he wrestled a match against Duggan. Before the match, he once again sang the national anthem of the Soviet Union and riled up the crowd.\n\nVolkoff made his first appearance on WWE television in over two years on the August 13, 2007 episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' as a contestant on WWE Idol, a parody of ''[[American Idol]]''. Volkoff appeared alongside the Iron Sheik and [[Howard Finkel]], although Volkoff was the only one who sang. Volkoff sang the Soviet Union national anthem, receiving boos from the crowd (despite being a babyface) and was insulted by judge [[Darren Matthews|William Regal]], although judges [[Mick Foley]] and [[Maria Kanellis|Maria]] both praised the performance. In response, Sheik, who was also insulted, went on a tirade until both he and Volkoff were escorted out of the building by security.\n\nThe March 10, 2008 edition of ''WWE Raw'', featured rematches from previous [[WrestleMania]]s. The Iron Sheik appeared along with Nikolai Volkoff to face off against the U.S. Express in a rematch from the [[WrestleMania 1|first WrestleMania]]. However, the match never got started as [[Jillian Hall]] came out to interrupt Volkoff's singing so she could sing [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s \"[[Born in the U.S.A. (song)|Born in the U.S.A.]]\", which the U.S. Express used as their ring entrance music in 1984\u201385.\n\nOn the November 15, 2010, edition of ''Raw'', as part of the \"old school\" theme, Volkoff appeared with the Iron Sheik, singing the Soviet national anthem before being interrupted by [[Santino Marella]] and [[Vladimir Kozlov]], the latter of whom then sung a duet with Volkoff of the Soviet national anthem.\n\nAfterwards, Volkoff worked for various [[independent circuit|independent promotions]] throughout North America. He remained popular on the autograph convention circuit. In June 2013 he threw out the first pitch at a Bowie Baysox baseball game and sang \"God Bless America\" after the pitch. In October 2013, he sang the Soviet national anthem at a show in New Jersey, after being introduced by [[Howard Finkel]].\n\nVolkoff lent his name to a forward for a fiction novel called \"Only The Beginning\" which is set in the 1980s and is about a girl's life during high school. While the book is not wrestling related, the author Jason Strecker was a personal friend of Volkoff's and in the foreword Volkoff responds to his friendship with the author along with the book's message of being of strong character and doing positive actions for others. The book also has a foreword by [[Jimmy Valiant]].\n\nOn the January 6, 2014 \"Old School\" episode of ''RAW'', Volkoff encountered [[Big E (wrestler)|Big E. Langston]] on his way to a match and sung him the Soviet national anthem, to which Langston smiled. Immediately after, Langston walked past fellow Million Dollar Corporation members, [[Ted DiBiase]] and [[Mike Rotunda|Irwin R. Schyster]].\n\nOn the RAW Fallout segment following the September 8, 2014 ''Raw'', Volkoff appeared backstage with [[Rusev (wrestler)|Rusev]] and [[Lana (wrestling)|Lana]] and sang the Soviet national anthem.<ref>{{Citation|last=WWE|title=Nikolai Volkoff joins Rusev & Lana - Raw Fallout - Sept. 8, 2014|date=September 8, 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8WobMoezcP8|accessdate=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2015, Volkoff appeared for the Superstars of Wrestling promotion in Bayville, New Jersey, where he teamed with ECW legend [[The Sandman (wrestler)|The Sandman]] to take on independent standouts Kentucky Bred \u2013 in a 3 on 2 handicap tag match. Before the match, Volkoff and Sandman sang the Soviet national anthem and proceeded to drink beer together. The duo squashed Kentucky Bred and then poured beer all over them.\n\nOn March 21, 2015, Volkoff participated at a SICW event taking place on East Carondelet. Volkoff managed and mentored the team of younger wrestlers Ricky Cruz and Red River Jack, while also managing veteran wrestler \"Cowboy\" Bob Orton Jr. to take on the team of Chris Hargas, Bull Bronson, and Attila Khan. Volkoff and Orton appeared in their outfit and gimmick from their WWF days. The team of Volkoff, Orton, Cruz, and Jack came up victorious.\n\nOn March 5, 2016, Volkoff showed up at Night of Legends at Billtown Wrestling in Williamsport, Pennsylvania, sang the American national anthem and teamed with Cash Money, who turned on him to give the win to Koko B. Ware and Jim Neidhart.\n\nOn June 25, 2016 he wrestled his last match in Canada where he defeated the Messiah for Great North Wrestling in Pembroke, Ontario.\n\nOn June 9, 2017, Volkoff wrestled for H20 Wrestling: 1 Year Anniversary in Willamstown, New Jersey as he defeated [[DJ Hyde]].\n\nOn May 5, 2018, at the age of 70, Volkoff wrestled his final match, teaming with [[Jim Duggan]] to defeated the team of Mecha Mercenary and [[Nick Berk|Nicky Benz]] for Battleground Championship Wrestling in Feasterville, Pennsylvania.\n\n==Personal life and death==\nPeruzovi\u0107 met his wife Lynn in 1970, and became an American citizen that year.<ref name=\"Vensel\">{{cite news|last1=Vensel|first1=Matt|title=Retired professional wrestler Nikolai Volkoff turns his energy to helping children |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/sports/bs-sp-nikolai-volkoff-profile-20130910-story.html|accessdate=July 29, 2018|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|publisher=[[tronc|Tronc, Inc.]]|location=[[Baltimore]]|date=September 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mywebpal.com/news_tool_v2.cfm?pnpid=659&show=archivedetails&ArchiveID=1098203&om=1|title=Ex-wrestler finds code of conduct|date=March 30, 2005|last=Sears|first=Bryan P.|work=Towson Times|location=[[Walla Walla, Washington]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926213111/http://news.mywebpal.com/news_tool_v2.cfm?pnpid=659&show=archivedetails&ArchiveID=1098203&om=1|archivedate=September 26, 2007}}</ref> In Freddie Blassie's [[autobiography]] ''Listen, You Pencil Neck Geeks'', [[Freddie Blassie]] describes Peruzovi\u0107 as a \"good family man\" who helped Blassie reconnect with a daughter from whom he had been estranged for many years. In a 2009 shoot interview released by Pro Wrestling Diary on DVD, Peruzovi\u0107 discusses in-depth his history with Freddie Blassie as well as helping Blassie re-connect with his daughter.\n\nPeruzovi\u0107 worked with the [[Baltimore County, Maryland|Baltimore County]] [[Police Athletic League]] kids programs.<ref name=\"Vensel\"/> He previously worked as a [[code enforcement]] officer in [[Baltimore County, Maryland|Baltimore County]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/iron-sheik--the-man-behind-the-mask-224707360.html;_ylt=Ajd1UiC.g8.fZ7oXwqR62zusFWFH;_ylu=X3oDMTIyYWNucDR0BG1pdANIQ01PTCBvbiBhcnRpY2xlIHJpZ2h0IHJhaWwEcGtnA2lkLTMzNjcxMzgEcG9zAzMEc2VjA2hjbQR2ZXIDNA--;_ylg=X3oDMTBhYWM1a2sxBGxhbmcDZW4tVVM-;_ylv=3|title=The cruel tragedy of The Iron Sheik|first=Kevin|last=Iole|work=[[Yahoo! Sports]]|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|location=United States|date=June 23, 2013|access-date=May 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Fox\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,189119,00.html|title=Another Former Pro Wrestler Seeks Political Fortune|author=Capital News Service|work=[[Fox news]]|publisher=[[Fox Entertainment Group]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=March 25, 2006|accessdate=March 25, 2006|author-link=Capital News Service (Maryland)}}</ref> His brother is [[Luka Peruzovi\u0107]].\n\nPeruzovi\u0107 died at home on July 29, 2018, at the age of 70, days after being released from a hospital in Maryland where he had been treated for dehydration and other medical issues.<ref name=Death>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/119222/wwe-hall-of-famer-nikolai-volkoff-passes-away-updated-with-career-retrospective.html?p=1|title=WWE HALL OF FAMER NIKOLAI VOLKOFF PASSES AWAY (UPDATED WITH CAREER RETROSPECTIVE)|first=Mike|last=Johnson|work=PW Insider|publisher=PW Insider, LLC|location=United States|date=July 29, 2018|access-date=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nPeruzovi\u0107 ran unsuccessfully in the 2006 Maryland Republican Primary for State Delegate in District 7 (representing parts of Baltimore and Harford County) in Maryland.<ref name=\"Fox\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodricks|first1=Dan|title=Once-evil wrestler has quiet life in Glen Arm|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2006-01-26/news/0601260125_1_nikolai-volkoff-gorilla-monsoon-baltimore-county|accessdate=July 29, 2018|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|publisher=[[tronc|Tronc, Inc.]]|location=[[Baltimore]]|date=January 26, 2006}}</ref> He voted for [[Donald Trump]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mullins|first1=Luke|title=Nikolai Volkoff: Trump's No Kremlin Stooge!|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/01/19/trump-nikolai-volkoff-kremlin-stooge/|accessdate=July 29, 2018|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|publisher=Washingtonian Magazine, Inc.|location=[[Washington, D.C.]]|date=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Other media ==\n\n* Volkoff is a playable legend character in the 2003 video game, ''[[WWE SmackDown! Here Comes the Pain]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://ie.ign.com/wikis/wwe-smackdown-here-comes-the-pain/Legend:_Nikolai_Volkoff | title=Legend: Nikolai Volkoff - WWE SmackDown! Here Comes the Pain Wiki Guide}}</ref>\n* In 2010, Volkoff appeared along with wrestler [[Jimmy Cicero]] on Karlos Borloff's [[Web television|internet TV]] show ''Monster Madhouse''.\n* In 2016, Volkoff released a biographical comic book miniseries through Squared Circle Comics, titled \"Nikolai\" (2016-2018).\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Championship Wrestling from Florida]]'''\n**[[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA Florida Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Ivan Koloff]]\n*'''[[Georgia Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NWA Georgia Heavyweight Championship]] ([[NWA Georgia Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ga/ga-h.html NWA Georgia Heavyweight Championship History]</ref>\n*'''[[National Wrestling Federation]]'''\n**[[NWF World Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWF World Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Geeto Mongol]]<ref>{{cite web| last=Tanabe | first=Hisaharu | title= N.W.F. North American Heavyweight Title |url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/oh/nwf/nwf-t.html | publisher=Wrestling-Titles.com | accessdate = July 12, 2007}}</ref>\n*'''[[Maryland Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** MCW Hall of Fame (Class of 2009)<ref name=\"MCW-HOF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marylandwrestling.com/mcw/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=957:nikolai-volkoff&catid=102:hall-of-fame&Itemid=67 |title=Nikolai Volkoff |author=Maryland Championship Wrestling |authorlink=Maryland Championship Wrestling |year=2009 |accessdate=October 5, 2011 |work=2009 Inductee |publisher=MarylandWrestling.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625153912/http://www.marylandwrestling.com/mcw/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=957:nikolai-volkoff&catid=102:hall-of-fame&Itemid=67 |archivedate=June 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n*'''[[Jim Crockett Promotions|Mid-Atlantic Championship Wrestling]]'''\n**[[NWA Mid-Atlantic Tag Team Championship]] ([[NWA Mid-Atlantic Tag Team Championship#Title history|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Chris Markoff]]<ref>[http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/midatlantic/ma-t.html NWA Mid-Atlantic Tag Team title history]</ref>\n*'''[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Mid-South Wrestling]]'''\n**[[Mid-South North American Heavyweight Championship|Mid-South North American Championship]] ([[Mid-South North American Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])\n*'''[[New England Pro Wrestling Hall of Fame]]\n**Class of 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nepwhof.weebly.com/hall-of-famers.html |title=List of Past Inductees  |accessdate=June 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130706232003/http://nepwhof.weebly.com/hall-of-famers.html |archivedate=July 6, 2013 }}</ref>\n*'''North American Wrestling'''\n**NAW Heavyweight Championship (2 times)<ref name=\"Titles\"/>\n*'''Northeast Championship Wrestling (Tom Janette)'''\n**NCW Heavyweight Championship (1 time)<ref name=\"Titles\